      "value": "San Diego Unified is a large K-12 unified district serving 3,484 students with active IEPs, including 560 autistic students. About 85% of autistic students spend 80% or more of the school day in general-education settings, slightly below the 92% rate across all disability categories. Only 1.3% of autistic students are placed in fully separate special-education settings."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-16T07:19:45Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard"
      ],
      "value": "For an autistic child, the data shows inclusion-leaning placement is typical, with roughly 85 of every 100 autistic students learning alongside general-education peers for at least 80% of the school day. Academic outcomes for Students with Disabilities \u2014 a broader group that includes autism but is not autism-specific \u2014 sit 68 points below standard in English and 96 points below in math, while the all-students baseline is 12 points above standard in English and 19 points below in math. Chronic absenteeism and suspension rates for SWD (28% and 4%) run higher than the all-students baseline (19% and 2%). Because this is the largest district in the county, district-wide averages don't capture variation between individual schools."
    }
